  "action_title": "Use education programmes and local engagement to reduce persecution or exploitation of species",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nWe found no studies that evaluated the effects of using education programmes and local engagement to reduce persecution or exploitation of butterflies and moths.\n\n\u2018We found no studies\u2019 means that we have not yet found any studies that have directly evaluated this action during our systematic journal and report searches. Therefore we have been unable to assess whether or not the action is effective or has any harmful impacts. Please get in touch if you know of such a study for this action."
}

{
  "query": "What is the evidence for the effectiveness of engaging the public in amphibian conservation efforts in Europe and the USA?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from amphibian conservation efforts demonstrates significant volunteer engagement and participation across Europe and North America. Citizen science projects have successfully engaged substantial numbers of volunteers, with programs involving 100-10,506 volunteers active across 16-17 US states, conducting 412 surveys at 121-7,872 sites and swabbing nearly 6,000 amphibians. Habitat management programs with volunteer participation have shown positive population impacts, with two before-and-after studies in Estonia and Taiwan showing increased natterjack toad and Taipei frog populations, along with the engagement of 8-41,000 volunteers who restored up to 1,023 ponds or over 11,500 km\u00b2 of habitat. Public awareness campaigns have reached over 50,000 members of the public annually and trained 1,016 people at 57 events over four years, with awareness interventions increasing tourist knowledge of axolotls in Mexico. Amphibian road crossing patrols have been highly effective in moving large numbers of animals, with programs relocating 7,532 toads before/after breeding to half a million during breeding migrations annually across Germany, the UK and Italy, involving over 400 patrols in the UK alone operating for up to 10 years with 71 patrols averaging 90 person-hours.",
