{"query": "What are the overall success rates for establishing new amphibian populations through translocation or the release of captive-bred individuals?", "summary": "Based on global reviews and studies, amphibian translocations show moderate success rates. One global review found that 35 of 54 (65%) amphibian translocations resulted in established breeding populations or substantial recruitment to the adult population. Another review found that success rates were higher when translocations involved over 1,000 animals, but success was not related to whether animals were from wild or captive sources, life-stage, continent, or reason for translocation.

For specific amphibian species, studies on natterjack toads showed variable results: translocated eggs, tadpoles, juveniles, or adults established breeding populations in 30-70% of cases. Head-starting programs for amphibians showed mixed success, with six of ten studies finding that released head-started animals established breeding populations or increased populations, while two studies found mixed results and two found no establishment of breeding populations.

However, captive-bred green and golden bell frog releases showed poor outcomes, with studies finding that captive-bred frogs released mainly as tadpoles did not establish breeding populations, or only established stable breeding populations following one of four release programmes. Overall, while some amphibian translocations achieve success, the establishment of new populations through either translocation or release of captive-bred individuals appears to be challenging, with success rates varying significantly between species and programs.", "action_ids": ["854", "859", "881", "872"]}

