{
  "query": "What are the documented impacts of using prescribed fire on amphibian populations in US forest and grassland habitats?",
  "relevant_summary": "In US forests, prescribed fire effects on amphibian populations are variable. Eight of 14 studies found no effect of prescribed forest fires on amphibian abundance or species numbers. Four studies found mixed effects depending on species, year, or season of burn, with three studies showing fires increased amphibian abundance or species numbers, while one found abundance decreased with fires. Two studies found that amphibian species numbers and abundance either increased or decreased with time since prescribed forest fires. One study found spotted salamander hatching success increased following a prescribed forest fire.\n\nIn grassland habitats, prescribed fire shows more consistently negative impacts on amphibians. Two studies found that annual prescribed fires decreased amphibian species numbers and abundance, or increased rates of species loss when combined with grazing regime changes. One replicated study found that spring burns decreased salamander abundance, while autumn and winter burns showed no effect.",
