{
  "action_id": "848",
  "action_title": "Captive breeding toads",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nTen replicated studies (including three small studies) in Germany, Italy, Spain, the UK and USA\u00a0found that toads produced eggs in captivity, in one case by second generation captive females. Eight found that captive-bred toads were raised successfully to tadpoles, toadlets or adults in captivity. Two found that most toads died after hatching or after metamorphosis. Two reviews found mixed results with four species of toad or 21% of captive populations of Puerto Rican crested toad breeding successfully in captivity.\nFour replicated studies in Germany, Spain and the USA found that reproductive success of captive toads was affected by tank humidity or was higher in outdoor enclosures than indoor tanks. One replicated study in Germany found that survival of European red-bellied toad eggs, tadpoles and juveniles was higher in captivity than the wild."
}

{
  "action_id": "873",
  "action_title": "Release captive-bred Mallorcan midwife toads",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nThree studies (including one replicated study and one review) in Mallorca found that captive-bred midwife toads released as tadpoles, toadlets or adults established breeding populations at 38%, 80% or 100% of sites.\nOne randomized, replicated, controlled study in the UK\u00a0found that predator defences were maintained, but genetic diversity reduced in a captive-bred reintroduced population."
}

